configSetPrices.disclaimer:
Calculator

The information presented on this website is based on data available at the time. Design, specifications, price, and production dates are subject to change without notice and pertain specifically to Australia vehicles. Some features and options may be unavailable when your vehicle enters production.

CTP rates are based on the average 12 month policy from a sample of insurers. Rate is based on a privately used vehicle for a 40 year old driver with a clean driving record. Rates are subject to change at any time and without notice. Your individual situation may vary and have an impact on the final CTP rate.

Lending

4.75% p.a. comparison rate is based on finance amount $30,000 on a secured Consumer Loan for a 60 month term. This comparison rate is true only for the examples given and may not include all fees and charges. Different terms, fees or other loan amounts might result in a different comparison rate. Finance offer only available through Macquarie Leasing Pty Limited ABN 38 002 674 982 (Australian Credit License No. 394925) trading as Tesla Financial Services, to approved applicants (not available to fleet, government or rental buyers), subject to its credit assessment criteria. Fees and charges are payable. Full conditions available on application. Macquarie Leasing Pty Ltd is not an authorised deposit-taking institution for the purposes of the Banking Act 1959 (Cth) and its obligations do not represent deposits or other liabilities of Macquarie Bank Limited ABN 46 008 583 542. Macquarie Bank Limited does not guarantee or otherwise provide assurance in respect of the obligations of Macquarie Leasing Pty Ltd.

Wheels

There are different advantages to the 21-inch and 19-inch wheels. For example, the 21-inch wheels generally provide increased handling whereas the 19-inch wheels wear less quickly and provide more protection from obstacles and poor road conditions.
configSetPrices.resale_value_guarantee_text: Tesla guarantees the resale value of your Model S to be similar to or greater than other cars in its class. After three years, you can trade in your Model S for 50% of the original base price plus 43% of options. Learn more.
configSetPrices.incentives_txt: Electric vehicles in Australia have reduced Luxury Car Tax. Save over $4,570 AUD with a Tesla Model S relative to a similarly priced petrol vehicle.

PA01.name: No Paint Armor
PA01.description:
Protect key areas of Model S against stone chips, bug damage, weathering and other paint damage. Paint Armor is clear film that is applied to:
  • Exterior mirrors
  • Front bumper, fascia and hood (nose)
  • Front and rear fender (trailing edge)
  • Front and rear rocker panels
  • Rear bumper fascia

Depending on the angle of sunlight, seams between protected and unprotected paint areas will be visible, particularly on white and pearl white cars.

PX01.name: Performance Plus
PX01.description: Performance Plus adds world class handling to the incredible acceleration of Model S Performance, while also improving range. C_CHG_SUPER.name: Charging
C_CHG_SUPER.description:
Model S comes standard with an onboard charger and a 40 amp single phase wall connector. For charging on the go, Model S is compatible with public charging stations using an IEC 62196 standard connector. Charge rates up to 55 kilometers of range per hour of charge are possible depending on the power source.

An optional 10 amp mobile connector compatible with Australian and New Zealand type 3112 electrical outlets is under development and will be available in early 2015.

configSetPrices.gas_disclaimer:
Petrol Savings

Electric vehicles are less expensive to fuel than petrol powered vehicles. The average person drives approximately 15,000 km and spends around $3,100 on fuel annually. In comparison, the cost of electricity to power Model S over the same distance is nine times lower. Over the five year average length of car ownership, that’s approximately $14,000 in fuel savings.

Using the average Australian fuel economy of 13.7 litres per 100 km for a comparable petrol powered car. We’ve also assumed the regional average of $0.18 per kilowatt hour for electricity, 30% charging on Tesla’s Supercharger network enabling free long distance travel and $1.52 per litre for premium petrol over the next five years.
